47
00:02:08,441 --> 00:02:11,102
OK, so let's start by talking about what are games.

48
00:02:12,462 --> 00:02:14,723
So every storytelling medium,

49
00:02:14,843 --> 00:02:16,584
and games are a storytelling medium,

50
00:02:17,864 --> 00:02:19,105
like theater, like TV,

51
00:02:19,665 --> 00:02:21,686
every storytelling medium kind of lends itself

52
00:02:21,746 --> 00:02:22,906
to certain kinds of stories.

53
00:02:23,286 --> 00:02:24,467
So for example, books.

54
00:02:25,027 --> 00:02:28,728
Books are great at showing us the inner life of a character.

55
00:02:28,788 --> 00:02:31,829
We can go in chapter four inside the head of a character

56
00:02:31,869 --> 00:02:33,750
and listen to their thoughts for five chapters,

57
00:02:34,110 --> 00:02:35,230
and we don't get tired of it.

58
00:02:35,370 --> 00:02:37,831
It just is a natural expression

59
00:02:38,151 --> 00:02:39,732
that books really lend themselves to.

60
00:02:40,792 --> 00:02:42,853
So interior lives are in books.

61
00:02:43,733 --> 00:02:46,194
Movies are really great for visual storytelling.

62
00:02:46,394 --> 00:02:50,236
Big explosions, gorgeous actors, visuals,

63
00:02:50,316 --> 00:02:52,236
pictures really do the job in movies.

64
00:02:53,157 --> 00:02:55,217
TV is less about pictures.

65
00:02:55,638 --> 00:02:58,318
TV really is a great place where if you are a writer

66
00:02:58,358 --> 00:03:00,359
who is really good at creating relationships

67
00:03:00,419 --> 00:03:03,280
between characters and then expressing those relationships

68
00:03:03,340 --> 00:03:04,021
through dialogue.

69
00:03:05,001 --> 00:03:08,002
So knowing what different mediums are good at

70
00:03:08,102 --> 00:03:10,423
helps you know where you can do your best work.

71
00:03:11,265 --> 00:03:15,009
So games have kind of their own thing, right?

72
00:03:15,049 --> 00:03:19,212
And what makes games special as a storytelling medium

73
00:03:19,252 --> 00:03:20,113
is really two things.

74
00:03:20,413 --> 00:03:23,376
One, they allow us to create stories

75
00:03:23,416 --> 00:03:24,577
that players can live in.

76
00:03:24,937 --> 00:03:27,540
And for those of you that recognize this picture, yay,

77
00:03:28,641 --> 00:03:29,962
this is Point Break Live,

78
00:03:30,382 --> 00:03:32,224
which is a theatrical production

79
00:03:32,264 --> 00:03:35,246
that someone took the Keanu Reeves movie, Point Break,

80
00:03:35,727 --> 00:03:40,870
turned it into a play, hired trained actors, they perform every night, but right before they go on,

81
00:03:40,910 --> 00:03:46,074
they take a volunteer from the audience, just some random person, and bring them up on stage,

82
00:03:46,174 --> 00:03:50,417
and that person plays the Keanu Reeves role. Totally unprepared, doesn't know the lines,

83
00:03:50,497 --> 00:03:54,780
has to just kind of figure it out as they go along. That is game writing in a nutshell.

84
00:03:55,781 --> 00:04:00,284
So it's something really challenging about storytelling in games, and it's also something

85
00:04:00,304 --> 00:04:04,947
that's really special. So games let us live stories, and

86
00:04:05,514 --> 00:04:08,139
Stories bring meaning to gameplay.

87
00:04:08,359 --> 00:04:11,625
It makes what we're doing in a game matter when it's working.

88
00:04:12,387 --> 00:04:14,811
So stories have a really special power in games.

89
00:04:15,332 --> 00:04:17,596
And obviously, I'm a writer, so I'm biased,

90
00:04:17,636 --> 00:04:18,818
but I think they're worth the effort.

91
00:04:20,278 --> 00:04:22,741
You know, we have tools that other writers do not.

92
00:04:22,761 --> 00:04:25,104
I mean, one of the strongest tools as writers

93
00:04:25,124 --> 00:04:26,525
that we have is the gameplay.

94
00:04:27,166 --> 00:04:28,808
Sometimes we think of it as getting in the way,

95
00:04:28,848 --> 00:04:31,571
but it's actually like one of the most powerful tools

96
00:04:31,591 --> 00:04:34,034
that we can use to make an emotional connection

97
00:04:34,074 --> 00:04:35,236
with our players.

98
00:04:35,937 --> 00:04:40,780
And the flip side is, to my designers out there, that story is one of your tools as well.

99
00:04:41,660 --> 00:04:45,863
We don't always think of it this way. Sometimes designers think, oh, story's in my way,

100
00:04:45,983 --> 00:04:49,826
and writers think, oh, gameplay's messing up my story. But in fact, they're actually really

101
00:04:49,926 --> 00:04:54,529
powerful tools. The trick is we have to learn how to use them well. And that's what we're

102
00:04:54,549 --> 00:04:56,510
going to talk about today. So

103
00:04:58,037 --> 00:05:00,298
If we're going to get these two peanut butter and chocolate

104
00:05:00,318 --> 00:05:01,919
together, then the writers and the designers

105
00:05:01,959 --> 00:05:02,739
have to work together.

106
00:05:02,759 --> 00:05:04,040
Duh, right?

107
00:05:04,460 --> 00:05:06,721
And for people who are outside the industry,

108
00:05:07,641 --> 00:05:08,682
they'll often think, well, it must

109
00:05:08,722 --> 00:05:10,662
be pretty easy because you have a lot in common.

110
00:05:11,443 --> 00:05:14,564
Writers and designers spend all day problem solving.

111
00:05:16,125 --> 00:05:17,685
Writers and designers are both really

112
00:05:17,725 --> 00:05:19,866
interested in things like setups and payoffs.

113
00:05:21,447 --> 00:05:23,408
And both writers and designers really

114
00:05:23,468 --> 00:05:25,308
want to create an awesome experience for the player.

115
00:05:26,049 --> 00:05:26,929
So what's the problem?

116
00:05:28,844 --> 00:05:30,685
Well, we'll talk about that in a second.

117
00:05:30,705 --> 00:05:32,546
But I wanted to first share this awesome quote

118
00:05:32,566 --> 00:05:35,328
from Jesse Schell, who is one of my favorite people.

119
00:05:35,468 --> 00:05:36,088
He's amazing.

120
00:05:36,108 --> 00:05:39,090
And he talks about this idea that it's really, for designers,

121
00:05:39,410 --> 00:05:41,672
he argues, it's really not about the game.

122
00:05:42,252 --> 00:05:45,194
It's about the experience the player has playing the game.

123
00:05:45,214 --> 00:05:47,635
And you really could replace games

124
00:05:47,735 --> 00:05:50,937
with stories and designers with writers in this.

125
00:05:51,277 --> 00:05:52,758
And the same sentiment would apply.

126
00:05:54,353 --> 00:05:55,614
So we have a ton in common.

127
00:05:55,694 --> 00:05:56,835
So what's the problem?

128
00:05:57,516 --> 00:05:59,117
Well, let's talk about it.

129
00:05:59,637 --> 00:06:02,920
So yes, we are all writers and designers

130
00:06:02,960 --> 00:06:04,321
are both solving problems,

131
00:06:04,762 --> 00:06:06,443
but we're solving very different problems.

132
00:06:07,084 --> 00:06:09,025
Writers are sitting there thinking about dialogue

133
00:06:09,065 --> 00:06:11,027
and character and relationship and structure.

134
00:06:12,568 --> 00:06:15,431
And designers are thinking about things like this, right?

135
00:06:16,292 --> 00:06:19,154
Both important problems to solve, both kind of unrelated.

136
00:06:20,654 --> 00:06:21,774
Something else that gets in the way,

137
00:06:22,415 --> 00:06:24,737
we've got the setup and payoff idea, right?

138
00:06:24,937 --> 00:06:26,758
Which is true, both designers and writers

139
00:06:26,798 --> 00:06:27,599
are thinking about it,

140
00:06:27,679 --> 00:06:32,423
but writers tend to think of it in traditional story terms,

141
00:06:32,443 --> 00:06:33,624
which is beginning, middle, end.

142
00:06:34,084 --> 00:06:37,147
And that's because human beings are hardwired for story

143
00:06:37,187 --> 00:06:38,388
to think of story in that way.

144
00:06:38,848 --> 00:06:41,610
So writers are thinking in a linear fashion often,

145
00:06:42,171 --> 00:06:44,733
whereas game designers are thinking in terms of maps

146
00:06:45,273 --> 00:06:47,055
and of spaces, right?

147
00:06:47,475 --> 00:06:48,976
Story is linear, game is spatial.

148
00:06:50,657 --> 00:06:52,920
And then as far as creating a great experience for the player,

149
00:06:52,940 --> 00:06:54,441
this is the real zinger, I think.

150
00:06:54,621 --> 00:06:56,623
I think when we, if you asked a writer, like,

151
00:06:56,663 --> 00:06:58,025
what would be the ideal experience

152
00:06:58,045 --> 00:06:59,106
you could deliver to somebody?

153
00:06:59,606 --> 00:07:01,488
They're going to talk about something like moving you

154
00:07:01,548 --> 00:07:03,290
the way Shakespeare moves audiences.

155
00:07:04,051 --> 00:07:05,192
And if you ask a designer, like,

156
00:07:05,272 --> 00:07:07,475
what's the ideal gameplay experience?

157
00:07:07,915 --> 00:07:09,236
They're going to talk about something elegant

158
00:07:09,256 --> 00:07:10,778
and perfect, like Tetris.

159
00:07:12,029 --> 00:07:16,431
So we're both are looking at different North Stars in the sky, right?

160
00:07:16,551 --> 00:07:20,493
And so like the big question is, how do we get these things to actually start working together?

161
00:07:20,573 --> 00:07:24,054
Because if we don't try to make them work, they're not going to work.

162
00:07:25,808 --> 00:07:32,731
And I really think that the challenge in the working relationship is the perfect metaphor for it is the idea of silent disco.

163
00:07:33,332 --> 00:07:41,696
So if anyone's ever been to one, it's where you like hang out with your headphones and you dance and everyone else is maybe dancing to the same music, but you're really kind of doing it on your own.

164
00:07:42,576 --> 00:07:47,218
This is a lot of times how writers and designers end up working together.

165
00:07:47,830 --> 00:07:49,591
Like they're in the same room and they're,

166
00:07:50,231 --> 00:07:52,312
we think they're kind of thinking the same things

167
00:07:52,352 --> 00:07:53,853
or kind of listening to the same music

168
00:07:53,893 --> 00:07:54,834
as they create their stuff,

169
00:07:55,334 --> 00:07:56,775
but they're not even looking at each other.

170
00:07:56,835 --> 00:07:58,296
They're kind of doing what they want to do.

171
00:07:58,796 --> 00:08:00,157
They're both expressing themselves.

172
00:08:00,317 --> 00:08:02,618
One is expressing through gameplay and one through story,

173
00:08:02,978 --> 00:08:05,299
but they're not really communicating with each other.

174
00:08:06,080 --> 00:08:06,380
Right?

175
00:08:06,940 --> 00:08:09,342
And part of the reason this happens in studios, I think,

176
00:08:09,402 --> 00:08:10,842
is because both people are really busy.

177
00:08:10,862 --> 00:08:11,803
They have to do their jobs

178
00:08:11,843 --> 00:08:13,284
and it feels like it's going to be easier

179
00:08:13,324 --> 00:08:15,245
if they just do it side by side,

180
00:08:15,325 --> 00:08:17,026
but don't get in each other's way very much.

181
00:08:18,148 --> 00:08:22,152
But the problem is that doesn't lead to awesome creative breakthroughs and

182
00:08:22,232 --> 00:08:25,435
awesome innovations that bring story and gameplay together in new ways.

183
00:08:26,857 --> 00:08:31,261
So I want to argue that instead of being at the silent disco,

184
00:08:31,301 --> 00:08:33,123
we need to start thinking about partner dancing.

185
00:08:33,882 --> 00:08:37,903
Specifically, honestly, the tango is like the best metaphor I can think of,

186
00:08:38,123 --> 00:08:40,724
because the tango is an improvised dance.

187
00:08:41,504 --> 00:08:44,185
And while the man technically is leading,

188
00:08:44,205 --> 00:08:48,286
the dancers are really paying attention to each other and following each other's

189
00:08:48,346 --> 00:08:51,187
cues. That's why when you watch people dance the tango,

190
00:08:51,227 --> 00:08:53,747
the expressions on their faces are very intense.

191
00:08:54,188 --> 00:08:56,808
And it's because they are putting all their energy on their partner.

192
00:08:57,510 --> 00:08:59,432
to try to figure out what wants to happen next.

193
00:08:59,512 --> 00:09:01,594
It's not about the woman or the man.

194
00:09:01,794 --> 00:09:03,756
It's about the dance that happens between them.

195
00:09:05,218 --> 00:09:09,182
And that, to me, is the ideal that we all should be shooting for

196
00:09:09,262 --> 00:09:12,585
in terms of bringing story and gameplay together in games.

197
00:09:13,186 --> 00:09:15,127
So no silent disco.

198
00:09:15,288 --> 00:09:17,089
Yes, Tango. How do we do it?

199
00:09:17,850 --> 00:09:18,491
Let's talk about it.

200
00:09:19,704 --> 00:09:22,885
So this is the very practical part of our talk today.

201
00:09:22,925 --> 00:09:26,968
And like I said, I'm going quick because I want to have a lot of questions and answers.

202
00:09:28,629 --> 00:09:30,750
You know, it's not about what I say, it's about what you hear.

203
00:09:30,810 --> 00:09:31,491
So I'm here to help.

204
00:09:31,931 --> 00:09:35,653
So let me try to unpack three strategies that I've been able to use at studios

205
00:09:35,693 --> 00:09:37,935
that have really worked, that hopefully will help you as well.

206
00:09:38,875 --> 00:09:40,756
Again, whether you're a designer or a writer, it'll work.

207
00:09:42,259 --> 00:09:45,261
So the first thing I think is worth thinking about

208
00:09:45,941 --> 00:09:48,203
is making sure that the story in your game

209
00:09:48,383 --> 00:09:51,305
is really built around the way the player is

210
00:09:51,325 --> 00:09:52,065
going to win the game.

211
00:09:53,066 --> 00:09:53,586
And here's why.

212
00:09:55,067 --> 00:09:58,810
Because the players, in a way, really

213
00:09:58,930 --> 00:10:00,911
are the most important characters in your story.

214
00:10:01,471 --> 00:10:02,932
They're not there, right?

215
00:10:02,972 --> 00:10:03,753
They're on the couch.

216
00:10:04,793 --> 00:10:07,035
But their opinions matter.

217
00:10:07,115 --> 00:10:08,436
If they aren't engaged, they're not

218
00:10:08,476 --> 00:10:10,877
going to continue to play the game slash play the story.

219
00:10:11,467 --> 00:10:12,967
So we've got to factor them in.

220
00:10:13,868 --> 00:10:15,228
What they want matters.

221
00:10:15,328 --> 00:10:16,909
Their motivation really matters.

222
00:10:17,630 --> 00:10:19,971
And a lot of times, players are not motivated,

223
00:10:20,131 --> 00:10:22,072
especially early in the game, they're

224
00:10:22,112 --> 00:10:23,312
not motivated by the story.

225
00:10:24,273 --> 00:10:26,494
Players are usually motivated by the game,

226
00:10:26,574 --> 00:10:27,975
meaning I want to win the game.

227
00:10:27,995 --> 00:10:28,895
I want to beat the game.

228
00:10:28,955 --> 00:10:29,956
I want to finish the game.

229
00:10:30,856 --> 00:10:35,478
For a lot of players, story is a game progression tool.

230
00:10:36,675 --> 00:10:39,515
They'll go along with the story so that they can continue to play.

231
00:10:39,535 --> 00:10:41,176
They'll say like, oh, do I have to save the princess?

232
00:10:41,276 --> 00:10:42,216
Okay, that's cool.

233
00:10:42,696 --> 00:10:42,916
Right.

234
00:10:42,956 --> 00:10:43,796
And then off they go.

235
00:10:43,836 --> 00:10:46,057
And then if halfway through the, like, no, you have to kill the princess.

236
00:10:46,077 --> 00:10:47,757
They're like, oh, okay.

237
00:10:47,857 --> 00:10:48,297
That's weird.

238
00:10:48,617 --> 00:10:49,577
And then they keep playing.

239
00:10:50,337 --> 00:10:52,598
Most players are not going to be like, that's ridiculous.

240
00:10:52,618 --> 00:10:53,858
I said, I was going to save the princess.

241
00:10:53,918 --> 00:10:54,338
I quit.

242
00:10:54,918 --> 00:10:56,359
If they're into the game, they'll keep going.

243
00:10:57,179 --> 00:11:00,519
So we have to, and this is something that like traditionally, when I worked on

244
00:11:00,559 --> 00:11:04,600
projects, I would be siloed off with the story and I wouldn't know a whole lot

245
00:11:04,640 --> 00:11:04,980
about like,

246
00:11:05,810 --> 00:11:07,892
gameplay and player progression.

247
00:11:08,472 --> 00:11:10,194
And I think that was a huge missed opportunity.

248
00:11:10,234 --> 00:11:12,696
You want these things to be in sync as much as possible.

249
00:11:14,537 --> 00:11:16,138
So so let's say you want to do that.

250
00:11:16,179 --> 00:11:18,921
Let's say you want to make sure that it's like the players win state

251
00:11:18,961 --> 00:11:21,723
and the avatars desire line are in sync, right?

252
00:11:21,743 --> 00:11:23,965
