But like nobody sleeps through Bioshock.

490
00:23:58,707 --> 00:23:59,828
That's a really good example.

491
00:24:02,431 --> 00:24:03,792
We had another question.

492
00:24:04,193 --> 00:24:06,035
They said, hey, Susan, great presentation.

493
00:24:07,416 --> 00:24:09,719
If the writer wants to add something to the mechanics

494
00:24:09,779 --> 00:24:12,582
because it helps emphasize the theme and the story more,

495
00:24:12,642 --> 00:24:14,224
would that be crossing bounds?

496
00:24:14,505 --> 00:24:16,807
If not, what are some tactful ways to approach it?

497
00:24:18,257 --> 00:24:21,859
So sounds like, well, first of all,

498
00:24:21,899 --> 00:24:24,080
like that's definitely the way to be thinking, right?

499
00:24:24,480 --> 00:24:26,201
Like, you know, I think about,

500
00:24:27,061 --> 00:24:29,122
I'm guessing you're a writer person.

501
00:24:29,303 --> 00:24:33,144
So, you know, I think about our storytelling tools

502
00:24:33,184 --> 00:24:35,506
almost like, you know how when you see a cooking show

503
00:24:35,566 --> 00:24:38,447
and the chef show up and they've got their knife roll

504
00:24:38,467 --> 00:24:39,628
and they like bust it out

505
00:24:39,928 --> 00:24:41,368
and every knife's got a special job.

506
00:24:41,388 --> 00:24:43,409
This is my fish knife and that's my paring knife.

507
00:24:44,190 --> 00:24:47,032
And I think about the ways that we can tell stories in games.

508
00:24:47,072 --> 00:24:48,933
And I think of dialogue, for example,

509
00:24:48,973 --> 00:24:51,855
as the weakest tool we've got because players just

510
00:24:51,875 --> 00:24:52,395
don't listen.

511
00:24:53,095 --> 00:24:55,097
And then environmental storytelling

512
00:24:55,137 --> 00:24:56,077
is a very strong tool.

513
00:24:56,498 --> 00:24:59,159
And mechanics is a super strong storytelling tool.

514
00:24:59,760 --> 00:25:02,721
So I don't think it's overstepping bounds.

515
00:25:02,781 --> 00:25:06,504
But I think it really speaks less to the craft

516
00:25:06,564 --> 00:25:07,645
and more to the politics.

517
00:25:08,508 --> 00:25:12,750
because it's got to be an idea that both you and the designer can get excited about.

518
00:25:13,391 --> 00:25:20,935
Right? And so this is where being a really good team player comes into comes into play. Sorry.

519
00:25:22,956 --> 00:25:25,578
Right. But like spending the time and this is also like

520
00:25:26,138 --> 00:25:29,020
This is just career advice too. I've been talking to my friends who run

521
00:25:29,220 --> 00:25:31,782
writing teams at studios, and I'm like, what do you look for in a writer?

522
00:25:32,262 --> 00:25:34,784
And I was expecting a whole bunch of like, well, they've really got to know how to do

523
00:25:34,824 --> 00:25:38,727
branching dialogue, or they really got to know R2C or whatever. And they're like,

524
00:25:39,028 --> 00:25:43,451
they've got to be able to work with other people. That's what everybody says. And I was like,

525
00:25:43,551 --> 00:25:48,495
really? Okay. And this is a perfect example, right? So let's say you have a great idea for a mechanic.

526
00:25:49,709 --> 00:25:53,493
Then it just becomes a question of, like, how can I share this idea with a designer

527
00:25:53,533 --> 00:25:56,636
in a way that doesn't feel like I'm telling that designer how to do their job?

528
00:25:57,497 --> 00:26:00,920
Right? And so that's where, like, if you've got a level of trust with each other that you've

529
00:26:00,980 --> 00:26:07,746
established previously, then you can go and just throw some ideas around. And then, and here's

530
00:26:07,766 --> 00:26:11,530
the trick, and this is the challenge too, honestly, listen to what they say.

531
00:26:12,737 --> 00:26:19,782
like they might say no and and when people say no the temptation is to mount a defense like no this

532
00:26:19,822 --> 00:26:23,765
is a good idea listen I'll explain it again but I'll be louder this time then you'll get excited

533
00:26:23,845 --> 00:26:29,669
about it right but the smarter play is to just be quiet listen to whatever they say whatever

534
00:26:29,689 --> 00:26:30,669
their objections are and

535
00:26:31,270 --> 00:26:33,190
then go away and really think about it.

536
00:26:33,590 --> 00:26:36,171
Because everybody that works in game development,

537
00:26:36,191 --> 00:26:37,851
in my experience, is very smart.

538
00:26:38,271 --> 00:26:40,031
And when people have an objection to an idea,

539
00:26:40,051 --> 00:26:42,652
they usually have a pretty good reason for it.

540
00:26:42,732 --> 00:26:44,672
And that reason is usually, in my experience,

541
00:26:44,772 --> 00:26:46,593
rooted in something that I don't know anything about.

542
00:26:47,373 --> 00:26:49,133
Whether that's like an engine limitation,

543
00:26:49,613 --> 00:26:51,914
or like, you know the publisher will never go for it,

544
00:26:52,114 --> 00:26:54,214
or who knows, any of a host of reasons

545
00:26:54,614 --> 00:26:57,295
that have nothing to do with your awesome mechanic idea.

546
00:26:58,074 --> 00:27:00,416
but it's still going to be an impediment, right?

547
00:27:00,656 --> 00:27:03,819
So I think embracing the possibility

548
00:27:03,879 --> 00:27:05,801
of getting involved in game design as a writer

549
00:27:05,941 --> 00:27:07,962
is really important, and vice versa.

550
00:27:08,443 --> 00:27:10,364
I want designers to start getting really excited

551
00:27:10,404 --> 00:27:12,186
about being involved in the story process.

552
00:27:12,806 --> 00:27:14,888
And then it's a question of how do we do it collaboratively?

553
00:27:16,530 --> 00:27:18,031
And that takes time, unfortunately,

554
00:27:18,191 --> 00:27:19,993
but that's how it gets done.

555
00:27:20,813 --> 00:27:21,754
Like with anything, right?

556
00:27:22,296 --> 00:27:23,817
Like anything, right?

557
00:27:24,078 --> 00:27:24,718
Exactly.

558
00:27:25,859 --> 00:27:26,359
Let's see.

559
00:27:26,480 --> 00:27:29,542
So Nathan asks, can any kind of gameplay

560
00:27:29,602 --> 00:27:32,204
benefit from having a story and vice versa?

561
00:27:32,264 --> 00:27:34,827
For example, can a mechanics-focused game

562
00:27:34,867 --> 00:27:37,028
like Tetris be improved with a story that

563
00:27:37,089 --> 00:27:38,069
matches it well enough?

564
00:27:39,971 --> 00:27:41,352
So that's an interesting question.

565
00:27:41,452 --> 00:27:42,373
I'll be honest.

566
00:27:42,753 --> 00:27:44,935
I do not want to see a story Tetris game.

567
00:27:46,218 --> 00:27:47,580
Like, Tetris is perfect.

568
00:27:47,620 --> 00:27:49,001
Like, why would we add a story to it?

569
00:27:49,421 --> 00:27:51,163
What's exciting to me, this is actually,

570
00:27:51,183 --> 00:27:54,566
this will be a positive comment once I get around to it.

571
00:27:55,367 --> 00:27:56,768
Games don't need stories.

572
00:27:57,489 --> 00:27:59,691
Not in the same way that like movies need stories

573
00:27:59,731 --> 00:28:01,533
and TV needs stories and books need stories.

574
00:28:01,833 --> 00:28:04,496
Games are a storytelling medium, but they are not,

575
00:28:04,896 --> 00:28:06,577
that is not their reason for being.

576
00:28:07,678 --> 00:28:11,300
And so story is optional, and therefore, I think,

577
00:28:11,360 --> 00:28:13,401
as an industry, as a bunch of creatives,

578
00:28:13,441 --> 00:28:16,883
we should be being a whole lot more foolish

579
00:28:17,003 --> 00:28:17,864
around story ideas.

580
00:28:17,904 --> 00:28:19,705
We should be crazier and more creative

581
00:28:19,765 --> 00:28:22,707
and try nuttier things because it's optional.

582
00:28:23,327 --> 00:28:25,108
Like, if it doesn't work, just cut it, right?

583
00:28:25,128 --> 00:28:27,349
I mean, not to be overly simplistic,

584
00:28:27,429 --> 00:28:31,992
but I do think that not every game needs a story.

585
00:28:34,299 --> 00:28:39,841
But when story and gameplay really work, there is something special and magical that can't

586
00:28:39,862 --> 00:28:40,482
be replicated.

587
00:28:41,182 --> 00:28:45,244
And the other thing about this too is that gamers are desperate for this stuff.

588
00:28:45,804 --> 00:28:50,746
The Entertainment Software Association did a study of what motivates people to buy a

589
00:28:50,806 --> 00:28:51,066
game.

590
00:28:51,506 --> 00:28:52,746
What's your decision criteria?

591
00:28:53,367 --> 00:28:56,108
And 57% of them are like, well, if it's got a good story, I'll buy it.

592
00:28:57,397 --> 00:29:00,661
Like that's a big number, right?

593
00:29:00,781 --> 00:29:04,625
And so, and you know, all games out there

594
00:29:04,645 --> 00:29:06,427
like have a really solid code base

595
00:29:06,847 --> 00:29:09,190
and all games have great animation for the most part

596
00:29:09,290 --> 00:29:11,112
and great music and great game design.

597
00:29:12,073 --> 00:29:14,616
But the one place you can really stand out even now

598
00:29:15,136 --> 00:29:17,559
is if you can deliver a great game with a great story.

599
00:29:18,430 --> 00:29:22,211
It's hard to do, and so the ones that pull it off really stand out.

600
00:29:22,911 --> 00:29:26,732
And so even though it's hard to do, it's worthwhile and it can be done.

601
00:29:26,752 --> 00:29:30,412
And the reality is it's only going to get easier because we're going to, it's

602
00:29:30,432 --> 00:29:32,713
going to learn more and more and more about how to do this.

603
00:29:32,813 --> 00:29:36,314
It's, it's hard now, but it's easier than it was five years ago, which means

604
00:29:36,334 --> 00:29:40,215
it's going to be easier than now, you know, five years from now, it'll be even easier.

605
00:29:41,406 --> 00:29:45,168
I've just been nodding at everything that you've been saying, because you're making really good points.

606
00:29:45,208 --> 00:29:47,510
I'm just sitting here like, yeah, she makes a lot of sense.

607
00:29:48,811 --> 00:29:52,053
You know, I'm teaching, I'm teaching the writing for games masterclass right now.

608
00:29:52,113 --> 00:29:54,154
And like, we're just really going deep on all this stuff.

609
00:29:54,274 --> 00:29:56,175
And like, yeah, it's really exciting to think about it.

610
00:29:56,215 --> 00:29:58,377
Like, absolutely.

611
00:29:59,618 --> 00:30:01,219
Let's see.

612
00:30:01,719 --> 00:30:06,762
So Bradley asks, what are some strategies for communicating with team members who are not?

613
00:30:07,353 --> 00:30:12,035
who are not as story minded to encourage them to value integrating narrative into their work.

614
00:30:13,315 --> 00:30:20,678
Yes. My boyfriend is a designer who doesn't like story, so I get it. I really get it.

615
00:30:22,858 --> 00:30:28,820
So, I find that what really helps

616
00:30:30,564 --> 00:30:32,126
And again, this is the long game, right?

617
00:30:32,146 --> 00:30:34,467
This is like investing in the relationship with that person.

618
00:30:35,028 --> 00:30:37,349
But even people who like, say like,

619
00:30:37,449 --> 00:30:38,970
I don't wanna work on a story-based game

620
00:30:39,010 --> 00:30:40,932
are gonna go home at the end of the day

621
00:30:40,972 --> 00:30:41,973
and watch Game of Thrones.

622
00:30:42,573 --> 00:30:46,596
Or like, everybody loves story, some kind of story, right?

623
00:30:48,637 --> 00:30:50,699
And so I find a lot of times when I'm trying to talk

624
00:30:50,739 --> 00:30:52,040
with someone who's kind of resistant,

625
00:30:52,660 --> 00:30:54,401
I don't talk about the project at hand,

626
00:30:54,622 --> 00:30:56,263
but I just ask them like, well, what are you,

627
00:30:56,543 --> 00:30:57,704
what stories do you like?

628
00:30:57,804 --> 00:30:57,944
Like,

629
00:30:58,884 --> 00:30:59,725
It doesn't have to be games.

630
00:30:59,785 --> 00:31:01,486
It can be, are there movies that you like?

631
00:31:01,526 --> 00:31:02,966
Are there TV shows that you like?

632
00:31:04,207 --> 00:31:05,608
Inevitably, there's going to be something.

633
00:31:06,108 --> 00:31:08,029
And then getting to know what they

634
00:31:08,089 --> 00:31:10,690
like about those stories that they like and kind of digging

635
00:31:10,710 --> 00:31:12,991
in without being intrusive.

636
00:31:13,512 --> 00:31:15,993
But you want to find some common ground with them.

637
00:31:16,933 --> 00:31:20,035
And a lot of times, the things that other people love

638
00:31:20,135 --> 00:31:21,536
can become the common ground where

639
00:31:21,556 --> 00:31:23,297
you can start a really good conversation with them.

640
00:31:24,672 --> 00:31:29,966
And the other thing, so that's like one tip and the other tip I would give is like, like,

641
00:31:31,490 --> 00:31:32,192
be curious.

642
00:31:33,197 --> 00:31:38,458
Right? Like, like, instead of, instead of, and I've done this, I've been like, I can convince them,

643
00:31:38,578 --> 00:31:41,979
like, if I just say enough words, they're gonna, they're gonna, they're gonna bow down to me,

644
00:31:41,999 --> 00:31:47,861
and they're gonna accept that story really matters. But instead, like, you know, be the read,

645
00:31:47,901 --> 00:31:52,323
you know, like, like, just be, well, tell me why. Tell me why you think story's not good in games,

646
00:31:52,483 --> 00:31:57,564
and let them, let them make their case. And there probably is some nugget of insight in there that

647
00:31:57,584 --> 00:31:58,625
will be really helpful to hear.

648
00:31:59,744 --> 00:32:03,206
And then, like I was saying earlier, like going away and reflecting on it.

649
00:32:03,667 --> 00:32:05,708
If you can, here's the trick. Here's what we're shooting for.

650
00:32:05,928 --> 00:32:06,969
You want to get to the point

651
00:32:07,389 --> 00:32:10,311
where you can really see the problem from their point of view,

652
00:32:10,971 --> 00:32:14,994
like legitimately, like not a patronizing kind of way, but like, wow,

653
00:32:15,034 --> 00:32:16,855
they've got a good point. I see what they're saying.

654
00:32:17,916 --> 00:32:20,678
And the trick is as writers, you guys, like this is actually

655
00:32:20,698 --> 00:32:23,580
tapping into your superpower because writers.

656
00:32:24,700 --> 00:32:27,062
One of their superpowers is that they've got a lot of empathy.

657
00:32:28,496 --> 00:32:30,617
Writers have a real gift for putting themselves

658
00:32:30,677 --> 00:32:31,637
in someone else's shoes.

659
00:32:32,178 --> 00:32:34,018
So think about it in terms of like

660
00:32:34,819 --> 00:32:36,179
making a power move as a writer,

661
00:32:36,460 --> 00:32:38,440
like really getting to know that character,

662
00:32:38,460 --> 00:32:39,761
which is that person at your studio

663
00:32:39,801 --> 00:32:42,182
that doesn't want to do story and find out why.

664
00:32:42,202 --> 00:32:44,183
And then, you know, then you,

665
00:32:44,803 --> 00:32:46,664
if you can empathize with them, here's the thing,

666
00:32:47,304 --> 00:32:49,025
you know, this is a marketing message,

667
00:32:49,085 --> 00:32:50,786
which, but it weirdly applies to this,

668
00:32:51,006 --> 00:32:54,828
which is you can't be seen until you learn how to see.

669
00:32:56,944 --> 00:32:59,685
And all that means is like you've got to understand them first,

670
00:33:00,445 --> 00:33:02,785
and then they're going to be way more open to understanding you.

671
00:33:04,806 --> 00:33:05,986
Now, that's again advice.

672
00:33:06,506 --> 00:33:07,886
Yeah, it's longer.

673
00:33:08,366 --> 00:33:11,227
It's more effort, but it's it's how you win.

674
00:33:12,527 --> 00:33:13,547
Yeah, absolutely.

675
00:33:13,887 --> 00:33:16,768
We have a lot of really good questions, so I'm very I'm very excited.

676
00:33:18,508 --> 00:33:19,088
So let's see.

