00:36:06,522 --> 00:36:06,642
right?

728
00:36:06,682 --> 00:36:08,083
Like, how can we deliver a story?

729
00:36:08,644 --> 00:36:10,345
Here's how you deliver a story in a game.

730
00:36:10,845 --> 00:36:12,947
You figure out what the player is paying attention to,

731
00:36:13,007 --> 00:36:13,968
and you put the story there.

732
00:36:15,629 --> 00:36:20,192
So for example, players pay a lot of attention to the world.

733
00:36:21,263 --> 00:36:24,004
Because that's where the trouble lies in terms of enemies.

734
00:36:25,165 --> 00:36:26,665
And that's also where the treasure lies.

735
00:36:27,385 --> 00:36:28,386
That's where the loot is.

736
00:36:28,546 --> 00:36:30,506
That's the map they're trying to navigate.

737
00:36:30,526 --> 00:36:31,687
There's the bridge I was looking for.

738
00:36:32,027 --> 00:36:33,807
So they're real attentive to the world.

739
00:36:34,208 --> 00:36:37,169
So environmental storytelling is really powerful.

740
00:36:39,689 --> 00:36:43,090
And mechanics can be really powerful.

741
00:36:43,531 --> 00:36:45,431
And I think also something else I want to say,

742
00:36:46,031 --> 00:36:47,232
every answer could go on for an hour,

743
00:36:47,272 --> 00:36:48,432
but something else I want to say is

744
00:36:51,163 --> 00:36:53,944
You know, games are really, storytelling in games

745
00:36:54,004 --> 00:36:55,244
are really counterintuitive.

746
00:36:55,284 --> 00:36:57,205
Like if you've got a big story that you wanna

747
00:36:57,665 --> 00:36:59,926
really deliver to the player and it's real important to you

748
00:36:59,946 --> 00:37:03,448
that they see it, the best way to deliver it to them

749
00:37:04,388 --> 00:37:07,669
is to hide it from them.

750
00:37:08,189 --> 00:37:11,311
Like you wanna use what they call pull storytelling

751
00:37:12,231 --> 00:37:13,491
versus like push storytelling.

752
00:37:13,531 --> 00:37:16,513
So if the gameplay stops and I push a cinematic on you,

753
00:37:17,545 --> 00:37:18,525
Like you just want to skip it.

754
00:37:18,565 --> 00:37:21,227
Like it feels like an affront, like, hey, get out of my space.

755
00:37:21,287 --> 00:37:21,507
Right.

756
00:37:22,027 --> 00:37:23,468
But if you're playing a game and it's like,

757
00:37:23,908 --> 00:37:26,850
you don't know what's happening in this world, but clearly something is.

758
00:37:27,230 --> 00:37:28,091
And it's crazy.

759
00:37:28,211 --> 00:37:30,032
And you want to understand you can't figure it out

760
00:37:30,052 --> 00:37:31,032
and you want to know more about it.

761
00:37:31,072 --> 00:37:32,133
So you start exploring

762
00:37:32,153 --> 00:37:35,415
and then you find some notes here and there and whatnot. Right.

763
00:37:35,875 --> 00:37:37,456
That's pull storytelling.

764
00:37:38,076 --> 00:37:39,877
That's pulling you through the space

765
00:37:39,917 --> 00:37:41,258
so that you can discover the story.

766
00:37:41,738 --> 00:37:45,600
And if you turn story discovery into a gameplay reward,

767
00:37:46,220 --> 00:37:48,341
like, that's when things really start clicking.

768
00:37:50,082 --> 00:37:52,444
So I say, if you've got a great big story,

769
00:37:52,544 --> 00:37:53,924
hide it like an iceberg.

770
00:37:55,685 --> 00:37:56,966
That's a really good way of putting it.

771
00:37:57,566 --> 00:37:58,627
It's a really good answer, too.

