00:41:41,906 --> 00:41:42,706
So I'm gonna share with you

855
00:41:43,286 --> 00:41:44,687
the things I think are really important.

856
00:41:45,447 --> 00:41:47,508
And here's what's not important.

857
00:41:48,228 --> 00:41:49,429
Here's where I think it's really important

858
00:41:49,449 --> 00:41:51,350
to be really collaborative, plot.

859
00:41:52,648 --> 00:41:55,109
Plot is a shared endeavor.

860
00:41:55,369 --> 00:41:57,750
You have ideas about the plot, so does the designer,

861
00:41:57,830 --> 00:41:59,490
so does the programmer, so does the player.

862
00:42:00,170 --> 00:42:01,310
And that is great.

863
00:42:01,590 --> 00:42:02,891
It should be a group effort.

864
00:42:03,031 --> 00:42:04,231
Don't sweat plot.

865
00:42:04,971 --> 00:42:06,231
Let it be, right?

866
00:42:06,612 --> 00:42:08,252
Throw out ideas, make suggestions,

867
00:42:08,332 --> 00:42:10,332
but let it evolve however it's going to.

868
00:42:10,852 --> 00:42:12,913
The place where you wanna put your storytelling love,

869
00:42:12,933 --> 00:42:15,193
where you can be of greatest service to your team

870
00:42:15,954 --> 00:42:18,074
is by really committing to the characters.

871
00:42:20,444 --> 00:42:23,046
Storytelling in games is about character creation.

872
00:42:23,466 --> 00:42:25,808
And oftentimes, when I say character,

873
00:42:25,828 --> 00:42:27,089
I don't mean the player avatar.

874
00:42:27,129 --> 00:42:28,410
Like when I work on a project,

875
00:42:28,771 --> 00:42:30,612
I skip right over the player avatar.

876
00:42:30,632 --> 00:42:32,313
Like I push that guy out of the way

877
00:42:32,354 --> 00:42:33,935
so I can get to the NPCs in the corner.

878
00:42:34,710 --> 00:42:40,796
Because the player avatar is going to do whatever the designer and the player want to do, right?

879
00:42:40,916 --> 00:42:42,998
I really don't have a whole lot of control over that.

880
00:42:43,319 --> 00:42:46,522
And if I create a really fully fleshed out character for that avatar,

881
00:42:47,062 --> 00:42:49,985
that's probably going to get in the way of the player's experience, right?

882
00:42:50,005 --> 00:42:53,068
Because it's no longer them in the game. It's this guy or this girl.

883
00:42:53,749 --> 00:42:54,930
But the NPCs...

884
00:42:56,178 --> 00:42:58,519
Like that, those are your actors.

885
00:42:58,839 --> 00:43:00,920
Like those are the ones who are gonna read your lines

886
00:43:00,960 --> 00:43:03,581
and believe your story and embrace your motivations

887
00:43:04,041 --> 00:43:06,422
and live out the themes that you wanna describe, right?

888
00:43:06,502 --> 00:43:08,903
Like what we wanna do as game writers,

889
00:43:08,963 --> 00:43:10,744
and I'll maybe end on this note,

890
00:43:10,784 --> 00:43:15,325
like where we can do our best work as writers in games

891
00:43:15,385 --> 00:43:17,706
is if we create characters who have inner lives,

892
00:43:18,387 --> 00:43:20,667
who have like hopes and dreams and fears of their own.

893
00:43:20,727 --> 00:43:22,108
They feel like they are living a life

894
00:43:22,768 --> 00:43:25,069
and that you just came along at a moment in their life.

895
00:43:26,072 --> 00:43:29,654
to either be their best friend or their worst enemy or somewhere in between.

896
00:43:30,114 --> 00:43:34,998
But we love living worlds and living worlds are full of interesting characters

897
00:43:35,818 --> 00:43:39,901
and interesting characters are characters who are interested in something.

898
00:43:40,842 --> 00:43:44,264
So like what I would say to you and what I wish I could get in a time machine

